{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504063"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:10:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:10:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2296"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2296"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.66,0,0.17,0.16,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2296"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30461"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2296"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2296"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16403"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"6049"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"562"},{"type":"contributions","id":"588"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/30461"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with foot pain after a motor vehicle accident. On examination, his left foot is swollen with ecchymosis over the midfoot. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management of this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Orthopaedic referral with possible open reduction and internal fixation (ORIF)","Reassurance and discharge the patient","Pain relief and advice on weight-bearing as tolerated, follow-up in the orthopaedic outpatient department in 3 weeks","Posterior ankle splint and follow-up with orthopaedics outpatient department in 3 weeks","Posterior ankle splint, with no follow-up required"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows a fracture of the base of the second metatarsal and lateral displacement of the second, third, forth and fifth metatarsals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is a Lisfranc injury \u2013 a fracture-dislocation of the tarsal-metatarsal joint. A fracture at the base of the 2nd metatarsal is almost pathognomonic of a disrupted joint. The classic history of a Lisfranc injury is a low-energy injury, pathognomic plantar arch ecchymosis and the inability to weight bear. Treatment is challenging and may require an open reduction and internal fixation. Obtaining \u003Cstrong\u003Eorthopaedic referral\u003C/strong\u003E as soon as possible is necessary for any proven or suspected Lisfranc injury, as this injury has a high risk of developing debilitating post-traumatic degenerative changes and generally poor outcomes. Patients should be kept non-weight bearing until the review.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lisfranc injuries require prompt orthopaedic intervention."],"references":["Nunley JA, Vertullo CJ. Classification, investigation, and management of midfoot sprains: Lisfranc injuries in the athlete. Am J Sports Med 2002; 30:871.","Hatem SF. Imaging of lisfranc injury and midfoot sprain. Radiol Clin North Am 2008; 46:1045.","Stanislavsky A. Lisfranc fracture-dislocation | Radiology Case | Radiopaedia.org [Internet]. Radiopaedia.org. 2020. Available from: https://radiopaedia.org/cases/lisfranc-fracture-dislocation"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16403"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2296"}},"stemMedia":